    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-29T22:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-29T22:36:00-05:00" n="1015"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1015">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3430.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-29T21:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 29, 1912—9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Associated Press wire is still refused. The cutting of telegraph lines and the
                    undoubted connivance of the Government through indirect methods has arrested all
                    news except from immediate vicinity. Mexican railway cut twice, and cable line
                    cut last night. Mexican press reports surrender of Torreón without resistance.
                    Situation grows worse in Puebla and Vera Cruz.</p>
                <p>A new exodus of Americans from the city will begin and continue all through next
                    week, as it is generally believed now that the Governernment is likely to
                    fall.</p>
                <pb facs="0884" n="768" xml:id="pg_768"/>
                <p>The Orders of American Railway Conductors and Engineers submitted their ultimatum
                    demands to President Browne to-day. In the event that these are not acceded to
                    about 900 men will cease work on the National Railways.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
